Hi, Randy,

Essentially, the two options seem to be:

1) Say that what 6lo currently does is a perfetly valid exception (with
no need to do anything in this area in the future)

2) Flag what 6lo is doing as "something that doesn't comply with
default-iids. You may still use this n the mean time, but a solution
should be engineered to comply with default-iids"


My understanding is that Erik is proposing "2)"... and I tend to like
that option.

Thoughts?

Thanks!

Best regards,
Fernando




On 07/24/2014 01:50 PM, Turner, Randy wrote:
> 
> 
> Ditto what Erik said....we operate AMI networks where most of the EUI-64 threats do not exist, and 6775 mechanisms are employed - it would be nice if EUI-64s were not "deprecated" but still allowed, with the existing alternative documents being available for those that need it.
> 
> Randy
> 
