Hi,

Sorry for not being able to fully follow all IID discussions, but I think w=
e need to clarify the IID selection in the draft-ietf-6lo-btle-02.

What I mean is that currently the draft allows generation of random/privacy=
 protecting IID also for the link-local address. However, for me it seems t=
hat it would result in sending of ICMPv6 MLDv2 messages for subscription to=
 Solicited-Node multicast group and also ICMPv6 NS for DAD. It would be goo=
d to not require transmission of these.

I'm thinking whether we should actually mandate an IPv6 link-local address =
for Bluetooth LE link to be generated based on the Bluetooth LE device addr=
ess - which is guaranteed to be locally unique in the established Bluetooth=
 LE piconet. It's worth noting that the Bluetooth LE device address may be =
a globally unique 48-bit address, or it  can be a random device address sel=
ected by the lower layers in an attempt to hide device identity (and lower =
layers guarantee local uniqueness of the random device address).=20

I.e. add text that would be something like this:
--
   When the interface on a host is initialized, it follows the
   specification in [RFC4861].  A link-local address is formed based on
   the Bluetooth LE device address assigned to the interface as per
   Section 2.3, and then the host sends RS messages as described in [RFC486=
1]
   Section 6.3.7.

   There is no need to join the solicited-node multicast address, since
   nobody multicasts NSs in this type of network.  A host MUST join the
   all-nodes multicast address.
--
The non-link-local addresses could then use random IID (or other privacy-pr=
otecting IID) as is recommended.

What do you think?

Best regards,

	Teemu


